sentences: By October 1955, Down Beat magazine named her the "best female band singer of the year."
Richards married Kenton shortly thereafter, on October 18, 1955, in Detroit.

Richards' appearances on Kenton's LP releases for Capitol Records began with Kenton with Voices (1957), where she is a featured soloist on three tracks, including vocalese scatting on Gene Roland's Opus in Chartreuse.
She was paired with conductor Brian Farnon and arranger Warren Barker for her debut album, I'm Shooting High (1958).
The Many Moods of Ann Richards was then recorded with Capitol and released in 1960, with music arranged by Bill Holman, Ralph Carmichael and Tak Shindo.
In 1960, Richards was featured at Carnegie Hall with the Kenton orchestra and also appeared on Steve Allenâ€™s NBC-TV show.
Recorded at Capitol in July 1960, Two Much! was released in 1961, featuring Ann Richards with the Stan Kenton orchestra.
Recorded at Capitol in July 1960, Two Much! was released in 1961, featuring Ann Richards with the Stan Kenton orchestra.

By August 1961, Richards' personal and professional relationship with Kenton came to a quick end after she posed for Playboy magazine and concurrently signed a contract with Atco Records without Kenton's knowledge.
The cover of her 1961 Atco release Ann, Man! was taken from her June 1961 Playboy photo shoot.
The cover of her 1961 Atco release Ann, Man! was taken from her June 1961 Playboy photo shoot.
By 1962, Richards was in demand at jazz clubs all over the country, including Playboy Clubs, due to her pictorial in the magazine.
In 1963, Richards continued to have professional success, opening for George Shearing on a tour of Japan.
In June 1963, she appeared on the syndicated Ray Anthony Show as a featured artist.
In March 1964, Richards appeared as a musical guest on The New Steve Allen Show.
In 1965, she had a brief cameo as a bar patron in Angel's Flight, a lesser known B-movie.
Her last major singing tour was in Japan in December 1981.
On October 18, 1955, Richards married Stan Kenton.
In 1961, after six years of marriage, they separated and eventually divorced.
In 1961, Richards posed for a nude layout in Playboy magazine's June 1961 issue.
In 1961, Richards posed for a nude layout in Playboy magazine's June 1961 issue.
Kenton then filed for divorce from Richards in August 1961.
In late 1978, she married her second husband, Bill Botts (Frederick William Botts Jr.).
By 1980, the two were separated.
Richards struggled with drug and alcohol problems until her death in April 1982.

In 1980, her son, Lance Kenton, was sentenced to a year in jail and three years' probation in a high-profile case in Los Angeles for helping to put a rattlesnake in the mailbox of lawyer Paul Morantz.
Richards was found dead on April 1, 1982 at her home in the Hollywood Hills, her death ruled a suicide by the Los Angeles Police Department.
"In 1982 her friend Donna Shore organized a memorial for Richards at Carmelo's Jazz Club in Sherman Oaks, California.

sentences: Very shortly after joining the Kenton organization, Richards would record her first tracks with the orchestra on January 25, March 30 and May 15, 1955, at Capitol Studios in Hollywood.

The most notable and mature of these initial 1955 singles with Kenton come from a July 22, 1955 session: Richards sings two Bill Holman arrangements of the standards "Black Coffee" and "The Thrill Is Gone", recorded at Universal Studios in Chicago.
Kenton took Richards out on a first date to Glenn Wallichs' house in Beverly Hills to view a television pilot of Music '55, which sparked the romance between Richards and Kenton.
After this time, her singing career never regained the traction she enjoyed in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
